Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the pappardelle.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Add the @British pork and oregano sausage meat{225%g} to the pan and cook until it
starts to brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then
drain and discard any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Meanwhile, add the @pappardelle{200%g} to your pan of boiling water and bring back
to the boil.

Cook until tender, ~{10%minutes}.

While the pasta cooks, add the garlic and the @chilli flakes{1%tsp} to the pan
with the sausage meat.

> TIP: Add less chilli if you don't like too much heat.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1} @chicken stock paste{10%g},
@sugar{1/2%tsp} and @tomato puree{1%tsp} to the pan.

Stir together and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the @baby spinach{100%g} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and
piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain the pappardelle in a #colander{}.

Add the cooked pasta to the sauce and stir in half the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}.
Taste and season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

Serve the spicy pork ragu in #bowls{}. Sprinkle over the remaining cheese to finish.
Enjoy!